<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
15.0-60.0 cm tall, erect or spreading. Stem pubescent in lower part, scabrous, glabrous but with sessile glands in upper part; with 6-10 distinct internodes, the uppermost internode length 3.0-6.0 cm long and obviously longer than the next upper internode. Basal leaves oblanceolate 30.0-60.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.0-4.0 mm, pubescent. Cauline leaves linear or lanceolate 10.0-55.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-4.0 mm, pubescent. Calyx 11.0-19.0 mm long, campanulate at anthesis and clavate in fruit, pubescent; teeth unequal; shorter ones 1.5-2.0 mm, ovate, mucronate; longer ones 2.0-2.5 mm, ovate, acuminate; marginal hairs short (up to 0.5 mm), dense. Inflorescence non-divaricate, branch axile (much) less than 90°. Petal claws 6.0-7.0 mm long, glabrous; limbs 6.0-8.0 mm long, divided, upper-surface white, lobes linear or oblong, divergent, petal limbs cleft to middle or more, lower-surface green; coronal scales 1.0-2.5 mm long, obovate, apex dentate. Anthophore 8.0-11.0 mm long, densely puberulent. Anthers exserted; filaments 8.0-9.0 mm long, glabrous. Styles exserted. First pedicel 1.0-3.0 cm in flower, 2.0-4.0 cm in fruit, erect, glabrous, apex antrorse. Capsule 5.0-7.0 mm long, ovoid or ellipsoid, fragile, opaque. Seeds 0.7-0.9 mm wide, 0.6-0.7 mm high, testa smooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
E Egypt (Red Sea area, Sinai), N Arabian Peninsula, W Jordan and Palestine (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution map of S. sect. Arenosae. Each color code corresponds to one taxon: A S. arenosa B S. austroiranica C S. chaetodonta D S. exsudans E S. georgievskyi F S. leyseroides G S. linearis H S. microsperma subsp. cypria I S. microsperma subsp. maritima J S. microsperma subsp. microsperma K S. microsperma subsp. modesta L S. striata." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447291" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene linearis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has some superficial similarity to 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. austroiranica" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="austroiranica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. austroiranica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has narrowly lanceolate calyx teeth with narrow transparent margin, and not the broad rounded margin of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Different types of calyx teeth. A Silene linearis (M. Bierkamp &amp; P. Zinth 177 BSB) B Silene austroiranica (Rechinger 10772 B) C Silene corinthiaca (B. Oxelman 1934 GB) D Silene georgievskyi (Rechinger 9828 B). A, B and D are representatives of S. section Arenosae. Illustrations by F. Eggens." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447290" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene austroiranica" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroiranica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene austroiranica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is allopatric and found further south and east on the Arabian Peninsula, and in eastern Iraq and western/southern Iran.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The ranges of the calyx, anthophore and capsule lengths are unusually large in 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The large-flowered individuals are all found in Egypt (although not all specimens from Egypt are large-flowered), with calyx length of 17-19 mm (and proportional anthophores and capsules). The specimens are in all other respects similar (or perhaps with slightly shorter mucro on calyx teeth) to the 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens with smaller flowers, and we do not think the difference is sufficient to merit taxonomic recognition. The Egyptian specimens are in general (independent of flower size) tomentose to villous while the specimens from Palestine and Jordan are often slightly puberulous, although at least one specimen from Palestine is densely tomentose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
One sequence for a specimen from Egypt (
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, ID 49, KX757593) is included in the ITS tree. It forms a strongly supported clade together with the other two 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
accessions (PP = 1.00 MPB = 96% MLB = 93%, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the ITS sequences including 76 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447287" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
). The 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade (with the two Palestine accessions) is strongly supported in all trees (PP = 1.00, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Species tree from two STACEY runs and three unlinked regions (ITS, RPB 2, rps 16). Posterior probabilities&gt; 0.75 are shown above branches. The number following the taxonomic name is the specimen ID (Suppl. material 1). Scale bar reﬂects the number of substitutions per site." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447285" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">1</figureCitation>
; PP = 0.95 MPB = 75% MLB = 95%, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the rps 16 sequences including 71 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447288" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
; PP = 1.00 MPB = 100% MLB = 100%, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Phylogenetic tree resulting from Bayesian analysis of the RPB 2 sequences including 76 taxa. The trees were summarized in a 50 % majority-rule consensus tree with the posterior probabilities (PP) indicated above branches. Bootstrap support values (&gt; 75 %) based on MP and ML are noted below branches, respectively. The numbers following the taxonomic name indicate the specimen ID and Genbank numbers (Suppl. material 1), respectively." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.159.51500.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447289" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="nomenclatural notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Nomenclatural notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The name 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene linearis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Decne. has been used for a long time, but the delimitation of the taxon has varied. A number of authors have used the name in our sense, e.g. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.20323" author="Boissier, E" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B5" refString="Boissier, E, 1867. Flora Orientalis: sive, Enumeratio plantarum in Oriente a Graecia et Aegypto ad Indiae fines hucusque observatarum, Vol. 1. apud H. Georg, Basileae &amp; Geneve, 1-1017. https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.20323" title="Flora Orientalis: sive, Enumeratio plantarum in Oriente a Graecia et Aegypto ad Indiae fines hucusque observatarum, Vol. 1. apud H. Georg, Basileae &amp; Geneve, 1 - 1017." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.20323" year="1867">Boissier (1867)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" author="Rohrbach, P" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B54" refString="Rohrbach, P, 1868. Monographie der Gattung Silene. W. Engelmann, Leipzig, 1-249. https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" title="Monographie der Gattung Silene. W. Engelmann, Leipzig, 1 - 249." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" year="1868">Rohrbach (1868)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00695.x" author="Williams, FN" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 196" refId="B64" refString="Williams, FN, 1896. A revision of the genus Silene L. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 32 (220-227): 1 - 196, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00695.x" title="A revision of the genus Silene L." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1095-8339.1896.tb00695.x" volume="32" year="1896">Williams (1896)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Post, GE" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B49" refString="Post, GE, 1932. Flora of Syria, Palestine and Sinai (ed. 2). Ripol Klassik, Beirut, 1-639." title="Flora of Syria, Palestine and Sinai (ed. 2). Ripol Klassik, Beirut, 1 - 639." year="1932">Post (1932)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chowdhuri, PK" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="221 - 278" refId="B13" refString="Chowdhuri, PK, 1957. Studies in the genus Silene. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 22: 221 - 278" title="Studies in the genus Silene." volume="22" year="1957">Chowdhuri (1957)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mouterde, P" journalOrPublisher="163. Akademische Druck- und Verlagsanstalt, Graz" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B37" refString="Mouterde, P, 1966. Nouvelle Flore du Liban et de la Syrie. Vol. 1. Ed. de l'imprimerie catholique, Beyrouth, 1-563." title="Nouvelle Flore du Liban et de la Syrie. Vol. 1. Ed. de l'imprimerie catholique, Beyrouth, 1 - 563." year="1966">Mouterde (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zohary, M" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B65" refString="Zohary, M, 1966. Flora Palaestina, vol. 1. Jerusalem, 1-496." title="Flora Palaestina, vol. 1. Jerusalem, 1 - 496." year="1966">Zohary (1966)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlain, DF" editor="Miller, AG" journalOrPublisher="1. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 586" refId="B10" refString="Chamberlain, DF, 1996. Caryophyllaceae (Syn.: Illecebraceae). In: Miller, AG, Cope, TA, Eds., Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol. 1. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh: 1 - 586" title="Caryophyllaceae (Syn.: Illecebraceae)." volumeTitle="Flora of the Arabian Peninsula and Socotra, Vol." year="1996">Chamberlain (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Boulos, L" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B8" refString="Boulos, L, 1999. Flora of Egypt. Vol. 1. Al Hadara, Cairo, Egypt, 1-419." title="Flora of Egypt. Vol. 1. Al Hadara, Cairo, Egypt, 1 - 419." year="1999">Boulos (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. Other authors use this name for a more inclusive taxon, e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rechinger, KH" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B53" refString="Rechinger, KH, 1964. Flora of Lowland Iraq. J. Cramer, Weinheim, 1-746." title="Flora of Lowland Iraq. J. Cramer, Weinheim, 1 - 746." year="1964">Rechinger (1964)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4114408" author="Blakelock, RA" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="177 - 224" refId="B4" refString="Blakelock, RA, 1957. Notes on the Flora of Iraq with keys - Part III. Caryophyllaceae (including Illecebraceae). Kew Bulletin 2 (2): 177 - 224, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/4114408" title="Notes on the Flora of Iraq with keys - Part III. Caryophyllaceae (including Illecebraceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4114408" volume="2" year="1957">Blakelock (1957)</bibRefCitation>
, including 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. leyseroides" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="leyseroides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. leyseroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. arenosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. chaetodonta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="chaetodonta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. chaetodonta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. kotschyi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="kotschyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. kotschyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Boiss. (= 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. microsperma" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="microsperma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">S. microsperma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.10527" author="Sweet, R" journalOrPublisher="Bioinformatics (Oxford, England)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B59" refString="Sweet, R, 1830. Sweet's Hortus Britannicus: or, A catalogue of plants, indigenous, or cultivated in the gardens of Great Britain, arranged according to their natural orders, with references to the Linnean class and order to which each belongs (ed. 2), Ridgway, London, 1-623. https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.10527" title="Sweet's Hortus Britannicus: or, A catalogue of plants, indigenous, or cultivated in the gardens of Great Britain, arranged according to their natural orders, with references to the Linnean class and order to which each belongs (ed. 2), Ridgway, London, 1 - 623." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.10527" year="1830">Sweet (1830)</bibRefCitation>
used the epithet &quot; 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="linearis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; in Hortus Britannicus 2nd ed., in a completely different context, five years earlier than 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Decaisne’s">Decaisne's</normalizedToken>
description was published. The name 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene linearis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sweet has been cited by few authors. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" author="Rohrbach, P" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B54" refString="Rohrbach, P, 1868. Monographie der Gattung Silene. W. Engelmann, Leipzig, 1-249. https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" title="Monographie der Gattung Silene. W. Engelmann, Leipzig, 1 - 249." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.15462" year="1868">Rohrbach (1868)</bibRefCitation>
referred to the name as a synonym for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene cucubalus" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cucubalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene cucubalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wib. (= 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene vulgaris" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Moench) Garcke) and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/4109291" author="Marsden-Jones, EM" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B33" refString="Marsden-Jones, EM, Turrill, WB, 1957. The bladder campions: Silenemaritima and S.vulgaris. The Ray Society, London, 1-378. https://doi.org/10.2307/4109291" title="The bladder campions: Silenemaritima and S. vulgaris. The Ray Society, London, 1 - 378." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/4109291" year="1957">Marsden-Jones and Turrill (1957)</bibRefCitation>
recognized the name as a part of the 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene vulgaris" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-assemblage but used the name in a highly informal way. The name is not mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chater, AO" editor="Tutin, TG" journalOrPublisher="2. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="191 - 218" refId="B11" refString="Chater, AO, Walters, SM, Akeroyd, JR, 1993. Silene L. In: Tutin, TG, Burges, NA, Chater, AO, Edmonson, JR, Heywood, VH, Moore, DM, Valentine, DH, Walters, SM, Webb, DA, Eds., Flora Europaea, ed. 2. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge: 191 - 218" title="Silene L." volumeTitle="Flora Europaea, ed." year="1993">Chater et al. (1993)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Aeschimann, D" journalOrPublisher="Candollea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="57 - 98" refId="B1" refString="Aeschimann, D, 1985. Etude biosystematique du Silene vulgaris s.l. (Caryophyllaceae) dans le domaine alpin. Candollea 40: 57 - 98" title="Etude biosystematique du Silene vulgaris s. l. (Caryophyllaceae) dans le domaine alpin." volume="40" year="1985">Aeschimann (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pignatti, S" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B46" refString="Pignatti, S, 1982. Flora d'Italia, Vol. 1. Edagricole, Bologna, 1-790." title="Flora d'Italia, Vol. 1. Edagricole, Bologna, 1 - 790." year="1982">Pignatti (1982)</bibRefCitation>
or 
<bibRefCitation author="Greuter, W" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B23" refString="Greuter, W, Burdet, HM, Long, G, 1984. Med-Checklist, 1. Geneve and Berlin." title="Med-Checklist, 1. Geneve and Berlin." year="1984">Greuter et al. (1984)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene linearis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Decne. has been suggested to be conserved against 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Silene" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Silene linearis" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linearis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Silene linearis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sweet (Eggens &amp; al., in press).
